sentence-detokenized: The EU rejects Germany's call to boycott British lamb.
Peter Blackburn
BRUSSELS 1996-08-22
The European Commission said Thursday it disagrees with Germany's advice to consumers to avoid British lamb until scientists determine whether mad cow disease can be transmitted to sheep.

Germany's representative on the European Union's veterinary committee, Werner Zwingmann, said on Wednesday that consumers should buy sheep meat from other countries rather than Britain until scientific advice is clearer.
"We do not support such a recommendation, as we see no reason for it," - said at the briefing the spokesman of the European Commission, Nicolaus van der Pas.
He noted that further scientific research is needed and if it is found that action is needed, it should be taken by the European Union.

He said that the proposal last month by EU Agriculture Commissioner Frans Fischler to ban sheep brain, spleen and spinal cord from the human and animal food chains was a very concrete and precautionary step to protect human health.
Fischler proposed the pan-European measures following reports from Britain and France that sheep can contract bovine spongiform encephalopathy (BSE) - mad cow disease - in the laboratory.

But Fischler agreed to reconsider his proposal after the EU's Standing Veterinary Committee, made up of animal health officials, questioned whether such action was justified as there was only a minor risk to human health.
Spanish Agriculture Minister Loyola de Palacio earlier accused Fischler at a meeting of EU agriculture ministers of causing unjustified alarm through "dangerous generalizations".
Only France and the UK supported Fischler's proposal.
The EU's Scientific Veterinary and Multidisciplinary Committees are due to re-examine the issue early next month and make recommendations to the senior veterinary authorities.
Sheep have long been affected by scrapie, a brain-wasting disease similar to BSE, which is thought to be transmitted to cattle through feed containing livestock waste.

British farmers denied on Thursday any danger to human health from their sheep, but expressed concern that German government advice to consumers to avoid British lamb could affect consumers across Europe.
"We have to be extremely careful about how other countries are going to follow the example of Germany," said the chairman of the National Farmers Union of Wales, John Lloyd Jones, on BBC Radio.

Bonn led the effort to protect public health after consumer confidence plummeted in March after a British report suggested people could contract a disease similar to mad cow disease by eating contaminated beef.
Last year, Germany imported 47,600 sheep from Britain, which is almost half of the total imports.
It imported 4,275 tons of British lamb, which is about 10 percent of total imports.
A rare draft of Hendrix's song sells for almost $17,000.
A rare early handwritten draft of a song by American guitar legend Jimi Hendrix sold for nearly $17,000 Thursday at an auction of some of the late musician's favorite belongings.
A Florida restaurant paid 10,925 pounds ($16,935) for a draft of "Ain't no telling," which Hendrix wrote on a piece of paper in a London hotel in late 1966.
At the end of a January 1967 concert in Nottingham, England, he threw a piece of paper into the audience, where it was picked up by a fan.
Buyers also snapped up 16 other items put up for auction by Hendrix's former girlfriend Cathy Etchingham, who lived with him from 1966 to 1969.
Among them was a black lacquered and mother-of-pearl encrusted box that Hendrix used to store his drugs and which an anonymous Australian buyer purchased for £5,060 ($7,845).
The guitarist died of a drug overdose in 1970 at the age of 27.
China says Taiwan is spoiling the atmosphere for talks.
BEIJING 1996-08-22

China accused Taipei on Thursday of spoiling the atmosphere for the resumption of talks across the Taiwan Strait by Taiwanese Vice President Lien Chan's visit to Ukraine this week, infuriating Beijing.

Speaking just hours after Chinese state media said it was time to start political talks with Taiwan, Foreign Ministry spokesman Shen Guofan told Reuters, "The necessary atmosphere to open talks has been broken by the Taiwanese authorities."
State media quoted China's chief negotiator with Taipei, Tang Shubei, as telling a group of visitors from Taiwan on Wednesday that it was time for the rivals to hold political talks.
"It is time for both sides to start political negotiations...
That is to put an end to the state of hostility," Tang was quoted as saying by the People's Daily on Thursday.

Foreign Ministry spokesman Sheng Sheng told Reuters Television that he had read reports of Tan's comments, but did not provide any details as to why the negotiator believes the time has come for talks with Taiwan, which Beijing considers a renegade province, but did not provide any details.
China, which has long resisted all efforts by Taipei to gain more international recognition, was angered by Taiwan's Vice President Lien's visit to Ukraine this week.
China believes that the time for negotiations on Taiwan has come.
BEIJING 1996-08-22
China said it is time for political talks with Taiwan and that the rival island should take practical steps to achieve this goal.

Consultations are to be held to determine the time and format of the talks, the official Xinhua news agency quoted Tan Shubei, executive vice chairman of the Taiwan Strait Association, as saying late Wednesday.
July car registrations in Germany increased by 14.2 p.p. year-on-year.
FRANKFURT 1996-08-22
The number of first vehicle registrations in Germany jumped 14.2 percent in July this year compared to the same period last year, the Federal Motor Vehicle Office said Thursday.
In July 1996, 356,725 new cars were registered - 304,850 cars and 15,613 trucks.
These figures reflect an increase of 13.6% for cars and a decrease of 2.2% for trucks compared to July 1995.
Motorcycle registration for this period increased by 32.7%.
The rise is partly due to an increase in the number of Germans buying German cars abroad, while manufacturers said domestic demand was weak, the federal agency said.
Almost all German automakers recorded an increase in registration numbers during this period.
Volkswagen AG received 77,719 registrations, which is just over a quarter of the total.
Opel AG together with General Motors took second place with 49,269 registrations, which is 16.4 percent of the total.
Ford was the third with 35,563 registrations, or 11.7%.
Only Seat and Porsche had fewer registrations in July 1996 compared to July last year.
Seat registered 3420 registrations compared to 5522 registrations in July last year.
The number of Porsche registrations decreased to 554 from 643.

Israel downplays fears of war with Syria.
Colin Siegel
JERUSALEM 1996-08-22
Israel's outgoing peace negotiator with Syria said Thursday that the current tensions between the two countries look like a storm in a teacup.
Itamar Rabinowitz, who as Israel's ambassador to Washington conducted fruitless talks with Syria, told Israel Radio that Damascus seemed to want to talk, not fight.
"It seems to me that {(1)[MISC] the Syrian priority is still negotiations.
Syrians are confused, they are certainly tense, but the general assessment here in Washington is that this is essentially a storm in a teacup," he said.
Rabinovich is completing his term as Ambassador.
He will be replaced by Eliyahu Ben-Elissar, former Israeli ambassador to Egypt, politician of the right-wing Likud party.
On Wednesday, Israel sent a message to Syria via Washington in which it declared its commitment to peace and readiness to start negotiations without preconditions.
But she criticized Damascus for creating what she called a dangerous atmosphere.
Syria accused Israel on Wednesday of launching a hysterical campaign against it after Israeli television reported that Damascus had recently test-fired a missile.
It stated that it purchases weapons for defensive purposes.

"The message we sent to (Syrian President Hafez) Assad is that Israel is ready to enter into peace talks at any time without preconditions," Israeli Foreign Minister David Levy said in an interview with Israel Radio.
Tensions have risen since Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu took office in June, pledging to keep the Golan Heights, which Israel captured from Syria during the 1967 Middle East war.
Israeli-Syrian peace talks on the Golan Heights have been stalled since 1991, despite the previous government's willingness to make Golan concessions.
Peace talks between the two sides were last held in February.
"The voices coming from Damascus are bad, not good.
Mass media...
are full of statements and declarations that should cause concern...
This artificial atmosphere is very dangerous because those who spread it can become its prisoners," Levy said.
"We expect Syria, if it turns its face to peace, to respond to Israel's call to enter into peace talks, because that is our goal," he said. "
We do not want war, God forbid.
Nobody wins from wars. "
Israel's Channel 2 said Damascus sent a "reassuring signal" to Israel.
She did not specify the source of the report.
Spokesmen for Netanyahu and Levy said they could not confirm this.
The TV also reported that Netanyahu sent a message to reassure Syria through Cairo, the US and Moscow.
Polish diplomat denies that nurses are stuck in Libya.
TUNISIA 1996-08-22
A Polish diplomat on Thursday denied a Polish tabloid report that Libya is denying exit visas to 100 Polish nurses trying to return home after working in the North African country.
"This is not true.

Until today, we are not aware of any nurse who is stuck or held in Libya against her will, and we have not received any complaints," Tadeusz Awdankiewicz, Chargé d'Affaires of the Polish Embassy in Tripoli, told Reuters by phone.

Poland's Labor Ministry said this week it would send a team to Libya to investigate, but Awdankiewicz said the investigation was prompted by complaints from some nurses about their working conditions, particularly non-payment of wages.
He said that about 800 Polish nurses work in Libya.
Two leaders of the Iranian opposition met in Baghdad.
Hassan Hafid
BAGHDAD 1996-08-22
An Iranian exile group based in Iraq pledged Thursday to support Iranian Kurdish rebels after they were attacked by Iranian forces deep inside Iraq last month.

In a statement, the Mujahedin Khalq said that its leader Masoud Rajavi met on Wednesday in Baghdad with Secretary General of the Kurdistan Democratic Party (KDP) of Iran Hassan Rastegar and expressed his support for the Iranian Kurdish rebels.
"Rajavi stressed that the Iranian Resistance will continue to stand side by side with its Kurdish compatriots and the resistance movement in Iranian Kurdistan," the statement said.
The representative of the group said that this meeting "signals a new level of cooperation between the Mujahedin Khalq and the Iranian Kurdish opposition".
In July, Iran heavily bombed targets in northern Iraq in pursuit of KDPI guerrillas based in Iraqi Kurdish areas outside the control of the government in Baghdad.
Iraqi Kurdish areas bordering Iran are under the control of militants of the Iraqi Kurdish group "Patriotic Union of Kurdistan" (PUK).

The PUK and the Democratic Party of Iraqi Kurdistan (KDP), the two main factions of the Iraqi Kurds, have controlled northern Iraq since Iraqi troops were pushed out of Kuwait during the 1991 Gulf War.
Clashes between the two sides erupted over the weekend and were the most serious fighting since a US-backed ceasefire last year.
Mujahid Khalq said that Iranian troops have also shelled KDP positions in Qasri district of Sulaymaniyah province near the Iranian border over the past two days.
According to him, about 100 Iraqi Kurds were killed or wounded in the attack.
Both Iran and Turkey have been conducting air and ground strikes on targets in northern Iraq in pursuit of their own Kurdish rebels.
The US-led air force in southern Turkey is protecting Iraqi Kurds from possible attacks by Baghdad forces.
The Saudi riyal is stable amid quiet summer trade.
The spot exchange rate of the Saudi riyal against the dollar and interbank deposit rates in riyals were mostly stable this week during quiet summer trading, dealers in the kingdom said.
"There were no changes in the Saudi Riyal exchange rate.
The market was very quiet because of the summer holidays," - one of the dealers said.
The spot exchange rate of the rial was set at 3.7504 / 06 per dollar.
One-month interbank deposits are placed at 5-1/2, 3/8%, three-month - at 5-5/8, 1/2%, six-month - at 5-3/4, 5/8%.
One-year funds were at six, 5-7/8 percent.
Israel approved Arafat's flight to the West Bank.
JERUSALEM 1996-08-22
Israel allowed Palestinian President Yasser Arafat to fly over its territory to the West Bank on Thursday, ending a brief crisis between Israel and the PLO, an adviser to Arafat said.
"The problem is solved.
The president's plane has received permission to fly through Israeli airspace, but the president is not expected to leave for the West Bank until Monday," Nabil Abu-Radaina told Reuters.

Arafat was scheduled to meet with former Israeli Prime Minister Shimon Peres in the West Bank city of Ramallah on Thursday, but the venue was changed to Gaza after Israel refused to allow the Palestinian leader's helicopters to fly.
Palestinian officials accused right-wing Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu of trying to stop the Ramallah meeting by keeping Arafat under house arrest.
Subsequently, Arafat cancelled a meeting between Israeli and PLO officials on civilian issues at the Allenby Bridge, which connects Jordan and the West Bank.
Abu-Radaina said Arafat decided not to fly to the West Bank on Thursday, after Israel lifted the ban, because he had a busy schedule in Gaza and would not be free until Monday.
Arafat to meet Peres in Gaza after flight ban.
JERUSALEM 1996-08-22

Yasser Arafat will meet with Shimon Peres in Gaza on Thursday after Palestinians said the right-wing Israeli government barred the Palestinian leader from flying to the West Bank for talks with the former prime minister.
